<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by UCL Engineering (WSC059)</title></head><body><div><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UCL Engineering</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (WSC059)</span></h1><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Executive summary</span></h2><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Statistics and evidence gathered for this submission suggests there are still issues to be addressed on the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">journey to women’s full participation in the engineering academic workforce. That while progress has been made over the last 15 years the journey is not yet complete. Some of these issues are generic across higher education and STEM departments and others </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may be more pertinent to engineering faculties where the proportion of women is more marked.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The key issues identified</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> continue to be:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 66.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Challenge of dual careers in STEM disciplines</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Cultural tendency for women to marry slightly older men who are more likely</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to be further ahead in their career</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 66.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Managing maternity and return to a research based career</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Gender differences in assignment of management and pastoral roles</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 66.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Part time and flexible working opportunities</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 65.41pt; padding-left:6.59pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Sexism</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Recognition and award schemes such as Athena</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> SWAN have raised the profile of issues and helped to gather evidence and good practice. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While UCL Engineering continues to deliver on the inclusive engineering agenda from increasing the diversity of our students through to retention and advancement of ou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r staff we believe there is more that can be done to provide evidence and support greater flexibility and career management across the HE sector to support dual career couples and extend research into workplace cultures.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The engineering institutions could</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> be called upon to help develop reports such as those undertaken by the Royal Society of Chemistry and Institute of Physics to explore more about engineering academic and industrial based research careers and to explore the transition and flow between both</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Further action from research funders to help manage career breaks and re-entry to academic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">careers is called for. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Further examples of good practice and case studies in engineering education and research environments and research into faculties and the c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ultural climate could add generic evidence to fuel further action.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Introduction</span></h2><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UCL Engineering </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">recognize</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that problems (and people) don’t fit exactly within the boundaries of one subject. The Faculty of Engineering Science, UCL Engineering, is made up of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ten</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> diverse departments, covering areas from designing environments that reduce crime to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tracking satellites in orbit. Working together, and with the rest of UCL and beyond, gives us the interdisciplinary perspective to find solutions.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UCL Engineering has</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> made a specific submission of evidence to acknowledge specific issues facing engineering in contrast to other STEM disciplines</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and to call for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">further extension of new research examining gender in engineering in the private sector workplace to look at the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> academic environment and help transfer knowledge  </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Contributions from across the Faculty have been sought to add ideas to what might be done to advance women’s participation in academic careers. Some of these are reflected in non-attributed quotes.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ubmission is in addition to the UCL Equalities submission that focuses on wider workplace issues.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">These issues have been rehearsed repeatedly and changed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">little for 30 years.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The main reasons my female students have stated for not remaining in academia after PhD are: short term contracts (and their potential impact on maternity leave and part time work), long hours culture, and the perception that all acad</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">emic women at the top are either superwomen, have partners with jobs that allow a mortgage and full time childcare to be paid, or are there as the token woman.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">postdoc career </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">transition </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">point is critical</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">move </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">out of academic career paths </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">at th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is point </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for a number of reasons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> often due to personal circumstances, but occasionally to do with perceptions of the requirements of the career and of them in that career. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Dual Careers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and caring</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I have seen women take a different career path when cons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">idering starting a family. It is still common for women to have partners a few years senior to them, making the woman the lower earner. Therefore it seems natural in the couple, especially when maternity leave is taken into consideration, for the man's car</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">eer to be given priority. Therefore I have seen women leave their postdoc positions when their partners gets a better job elsewhere, or take part time work for childcare purposes. Once out of the academic pipeline, especially when part time, it is very ver</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y difficult to re-enter when there is a constant stream of younger highly motivated graduates coming through. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nature of short term contracts for postdocs deter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women. The transition to a permanent post in academia tends to require a number of short </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">term contracts to be undertaken before a permanent post can be obtained. These are not conducive to dual careers and unfortunately many women are not prepared to persuade their partners to follow their career path, sometimes around the world. In addition t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ort term contract does not give much stability if women want to have a break for children. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">erceptions </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and complaints </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">exist of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women given tasks alongside their research such as teaching, administration and public engagement. All of which can further</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a career, but only when done in strict moderation early in a research career.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Workloads need balancing and comparisons of pastoral workloads compared by gender.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">cademic salaries</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, although not on the breadline, are not sufficiently high enough for full t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ime nannies, housekeepers etc (especially in London). So unless you have a partner with a very high salary or low flexible work hours, someone will have to collect the children from school. This job tra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ditionally falls to the mother.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The challenge of trave</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is an expectation of i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nternational travel either for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">long term post or for visits and conferences which are not very easy with small children </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">incur</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> added caring costs.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are very </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">few role models</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">especially in engineering </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">which may mean women find it difficult to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">project</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> themselves in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> those roles, although mentoring is becoming more widespread</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and can help</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hese influences are subtle and hard to change </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women early in their careers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, in common with early career women 30</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> years ago, do not perceive any issues.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Civil Engineering at UCL made specific efforts to recruit more women some years ago and the fruits of that effort remain today with women rising to senior roles. The department also introduced an inclusive curriculum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> using scenario and project based work which is delivered to the benefit of students and a more creative staff team.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This lack of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">identity for women as a senior academic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> / senior engineer further deters women from pursuing an academic career path as the st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ereotype or gender schem</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in their (and others’) mind’s eye does not fit the stereotype male senior academic. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">exism can make progress harder and it can be hard to prove for fear of damaging one’s career.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are perceived to have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">greater flexibility an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">wider variety of interests than men;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> this is discussed in the forthcoming book by Mills et al (2014) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Challenging knowledge, sex and power  - gender work and engineering</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in which women engineers are described as moving between teams for flexibility and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to accommodate career breaks and joining teams in which they are excluded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and disempowered</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> While building breadth rather than depth can be seen by some to be a successful career strategy it can also be a career disabler by those with more depth of knowled</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ge. Other career advancement strategies that can backfire are increased administrative roles.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I've seen careers of both men and women stagnated by increased administrative or teaching workloads. Often these people have shown a willingness and competence i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n these areas and therefore are seen as a good pair of hands to give more of the same to. There's a catch 22 when you know that taking on more reduces research output, which damages your career, but not taking it on when told to by your head of department </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may also lead to career damage.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">My own career was derailed by personal circumstances. I took a decision to move out of short term contracts into a permanent contract in university admin. I'm currently trying to pull my research back on track in my spare</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> time. My former research team are supportive, but it's tough when you're up against people with stronger track records who can dedicate more time to research.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I have seen a post-doc work part time, but who was unable to continue because she felt that it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> was not possible to continue a research career on a part time basis.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I have seen the career of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> female</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> colleagues hampered by lack of understanding by senior colleagues - some intentional, some not.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">When women leave academia, what careers do they </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?</span></h2><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women leave academia to move into a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ll sorts of careers. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While this may damage the diversity of academia </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">these skills may bring</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> analysis and robustness to other disciplines</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and sectors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In some disciplines the move may seem to be a loss to the discipline, but for example in m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">edical </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hysics many women leave academic and enter hospital careers. Here, they make a huge contribution to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> healthcare and use the skills they've learnt in academia. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">his choice is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">driven </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lure of a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">permanent contract and excellent pension and maternity leave offered by the NHS.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aving scientifically trained women applying their skills elsewhere is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> likely to be good for those areas, but it is a loss to science and engineering academia if they are not working in that sector - both as role models if women don't continue in science and engineering fields and also to bring a more diverse perspective to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the profession.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The consequence of this loss to academia can be great though difficult to quantify. The UCL Equalities submission covers this in more detail. Overall the diversity of thought leadership and problem solving </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">brought by having more women on a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> team </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is well documented in business terms and academia needs to be more creative about retaining these women for the benefit of other staff and also students.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">udents in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?</span></h2><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UCL has been delivering unconscious bias training through its management tiers. Filtering this down through to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">supervisors at various levels </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">can mean they are more </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">comfortable working with wo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">men and are aware of the issues that may be faced by them. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This needs reinforcing through reviews to ensure that women aren’t pigeon-holed into stereotyped roles or teams and their career aspirations are stretched rather than assuming their main intent is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to have a family and work part time.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">More examples of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">positive work-personal life balances and plenty of role models</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> need collecting – especially across engineering to showcase the ‘normal’ over the super women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> And diverse stories – including how dual car</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">eer couples have managed – should be included. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Providing a voice for women who have navigated an academic career – or transitions between academia and the private sector – may help to hear </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">about improvements that can be made</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to STEM academic career paths</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Take a zero tolerance approach to misogyny and everyday sexism. Have procedures in place so that women encountering such attitudes can voice their concerns without fear of career repercussions. Have an inclusive mentoring programme for all those women wo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rking in STEM careers - not just the ones on a standard lectureship route.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">More emphasis on long term employment, rather than short term contract associated with specific research projects would encourage women to stay. As would full support of family </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">life</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">know men who say they're off to a meeting rather than admitting that they're off to their children's Nativity play.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">” Former Chief Scientist David King admitted to this while in office.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Building a culture where it is OK for men to say they are doing th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e school run will help women to balance their roles with greater confidence.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Good practice is mentoring all academics equally, with mentors being prepared to go beyond a six monthly half hour meeting and actively push researchers where required - reminding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> them to publish or, after advising that they don't take on an extra admin load, making sure that the department management structure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">allows them to not take it on. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mentoring is a useful route, but should be available to everyone to help them to think abou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t their careers - there are significant numbers of post-docs who continue on from one short term contract to another without thinking carefully about where this is going to lead them. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ood practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> has been reported </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in a large research group where young </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">researchers are encouraged to take on areas of group research as their own, rather than have them considered as part of a senior staff member's project. This allow</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> them to flourish and write strong fellowship applications in these areas without feeling th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">at they are treading on other's toes.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are not enough permanent academic posts for all to end up as academics (and perhaps this is what women identify more quickly so leave before even taking up their first post-doc) </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Maternity leave should be fully f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">unded by the research councils and extra time automatically given to the PI if a researcher goes on maternity leave, so that they can return after their maternity leave to continue with their career. The contract system tends to mean that if a woman goes o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n leave near the end of their particular contract then there is nothing for them to come back to. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Sabbatical leave for one term automatic for academics going on maternity (or extended paternity) leave.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Proactively ensure that women are invited to apply fo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r positions. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Offer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">support and guidance, monitoring and a positive environment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and promote them with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">openness and fairness. Ensure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">flexibility for example, being flexible a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bout their family commitments.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research areas that have global relevance and require</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> broad skills and strong communication skills have been found to be attractive to women in civil engineering. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Gaining financ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ial management </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">experience whether </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a role on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a committee </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for the departmental budget or applying for and managing a grant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> but also t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aking significant responsibilities in the administration of research grants</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">just as in industry can be a critical career enabler for women. Finance skills for academics and especially women academics </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">need to be introducing in the early career stages.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">Wha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:normal">t role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?</span></h2><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The government should set its ambitions higher for the STEM workforce. In Australia 85% of male and female engineering undergraduates enter related work compa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">red to 59% and 39% or men and women in the UK.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A focus at the roots of the education system </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">- in revising the curriculum and careers advice in schools</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and profiling the vital work done in academia, humanising it more and helping to move it on from being th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e work of boffins. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Greater funding available for those undertaking part-time study and part-time careers.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is also important to embed inclusivity and strong team and leadership skills into the STEM education curriculum so that pervasive cultural issues p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">revalent in male dominated workplaces can be addressed early in the education system. UCL began exploring this in an HE STEM funded project Set to Lead and are continuing to do this within its development of a common engineering programme. This builds on t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he work in civil engineering where scenario and team based projects dominate in the way the curriculum is delivered. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Science council funding has moved towards funding specific projects or individual fellowships, rather than the old platform grants, which allowed flexibility on employment of individuals. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Further to this, unless you have an academic post, then only fundin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g available as PI is a research fellowship. These are intensely competitive. It would be good if all research funding could be potentially open to everyone. There are some very senior postdocs who, after writing an entire research proposal, must effectivel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y put someone else's name at the top. This is disheartening. Also, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ouncil rules state that PhDs must be ta</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ken up at a minimum of 50% FTE – this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">can deter women with childcare commitments from undertaking a PhD.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The engineering institutions could be called</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> upon to help develop reports such as those undertaken by the Royal Society of Chemistry and Institute of Physics to explore more about engineering academic and industrial based research careers and to explore the transition and flow between both.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Further </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">action from research funders</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to help manage career breaks and re-entry to academic careers is called for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 66.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Fellowships available for women who have been on maternity leave (or men who have taken extended paternity leave)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> or career breaks in addition to gre</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ater support for Daphne Jackson Fellowships</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Fellowships that can be transferred from one institution to another to allow women (or men) to follow their partners. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 66.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Fellowships for people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">whose</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> partner has moved a significant distance from where they are b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ased.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Further examples of good practice and case studies in engineering education and research environments and research into faculties and the cultural climate and workplace cultures could add generic evidence to fuel further action.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">model for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">honest a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ppraisal of workloads across a department by a neutral third party </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to help balance out over assignment of management to women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Examples of how and where this has been done would be helpful</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-